  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equations.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\dot{\\omega}(t)\n=\n\\frac{\\tau_{\\mathrm{em}}(t)}{I_T}.\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\omega(t)\n=\n\\omega(0)\n+\n\\frac{1}{I_T}\n\\int_0^t\n\\tau_{\\mathrm{em}}(t')\n\\,\\mathrm{d}t' .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $I_T$ be the Trawinistic moment of inertia.  \nAngular momentum is related to angular velocity by:\n\\begin{equation}\nL=I_T\\omega .\n\\end{equation}\n\nDifferentiating gives:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\dot{L}\n=\nI_T\\dot{\\omega},\n\\end{equation}\nassuming $I_T$ is constant over the interval.\n\nSince $\\dot{L}=\\tau_{\\mathrm{em}}$, we obtain:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\dot{\\omega}(t)\n=\n\\frac{\\tau_{\\mathrm{em}}(t)}{I_T}.\n\\end{equation}\n\nIntegrating through time gives:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\omega(t)\n=\n\\omega(0)\n+\n\\frac{1}{I_T}\n\\int_0^t\n\\tau_{\\mathrm{em}}(t')\n\\,\\mathrm{d}t' .\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nRotation is the accumulated response to torque history, scaled by the effective moment of inertia.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
